title: Appointments to Advisory Committee of the Partnership Fund for the Disadvantaged
content_text:
p>        The Government today (February 2) the appointment of 10 non-official members from the welfare, business and academic sectors to the Advisory Committee of the Partnership Fund for the Disadvantaged. The 10 members appointed are: Ms Ellen Chan Kit-wing, the Rev Dorothy 
Lau, Mrs Julie Lee Lau Chu-lai, Mr Ma Siu-leung; Prof Mok Bong-ho; Ms Theresa 
Tao Chee-ying, Dr Jimmy Wong Chi-ho, Mr Charles Yang Chuen-liang, Mr Yeung Po-kwan

and Dr Yue Kwok-to. The appointments took effect from February 1 for a term of 
two years. The advisory committee, chaired by the Director of Social Welfare, is to 
examine applications for the Partnership Fund for the Disadvantaged and all 
matters relating to the fund's operation. The Secretary for Health, Welfare and Food, Dr York Chow, welcomed the 
appointments of 10 members coming from the welfare, business, academic and 
district background. He looked forward to their contribution to the advisory

district background. He looked forward to their contribution to the advisory 
committee. The $200 million fund was established to promote the development of a 
tripartite social partnership between the Government, the business community and 
the welfare sector in helping the disadvantaged. Applications from welfare 
non-governmental organisations (NGOs) would be invited. Following is a brief biography of the members: Ms Ellen Chan Kit-wing is an appointed District Council member with long 
services in the Eastern District and has an extensive network with local

services in the Eastern District and has an extensive network with local 
dignitaries. The Rev Dorothy Lau is the director of Hong Kong Sheng Kung Hui Welfare 
Council which provides a wide range of welfare services. She has also served on 
the Social Welfare Advisory Committee. Mrs Julie Lee Lau Chu-lai is the chairperson of Parents' Association of 
Pre-school Handicapped Children. She is also a member of the Rehabilitation 
Advisory Committee and the Social Welfare Department's Lump Sum Grant Steering

Advisory Committee and the Social Welfare Department's Lump Sum Grant Steering 
Committee. Mr Ma Siu-leung, being the chief executive officer of Fung Kai Public 
School, is an expert in information technology and well versed with government 
operations. Prof Mok Bong-ho is the Professor of Department of Social Work, the 
Chinese University of Hong Kong and the chairman of the Boys' and Girls' Clubs 
Association of Hong Kong. He is very familiar with tertiary education and

Association of Hong Kong. He is very familiar with tertiary education and 
research relating to capacity building. Ms Theresa Tao Chee-ying is the principal of Hong Kong True Light 
College and assistant chief commissioner of the Hong Kong Girl Guides 
Association. She shows concern about community affairs and has assisted the 
Social Welfare Department in various district programmes, volunteer and youth 
services. Dr Jimmy Wong Chi-ho is the president of Tung Chun Group. He is active 
in both the business and welfare sectors. On the commercial side, he is the

in both the business and welfare sectors. On the commercial side, he is the 
vice-president of the New Territories General Chamber of Commerce and a 
committee member of the Hong Kong Chinese Importers' and Exporters' 
Association. On the welfare side, he has been the chairman/vice-chairman of 
several NGOs. Mr Charles Yang Chuen-liang a chartered accountant, is a member of the 
Social Welfare Department's Steering Committee on Promotion on Volunteer Service 
as well as the convenor of its publicity sub-committee. He has rich experience

as well as the convenor of its publicity sub-committee. He has rich experience 
in publicising volunteer services and fund-raising with the Community Chest. Mr Yeung Po-kwan is a retired school principal. He is very active in 
community services and currently serving in the executive boards of a number of 
NGOs covering a wide range of services. He also possesses rich experience in 
public affairs and is a member of the Health Care and Promotion Fund Committee.
